Introduction to Flask

5 steps

Flask is a lightweight web development framework that can deliver complex apps with minimal code. Here you will learn what Flask is, its benefits and its use cases.

Players will learn to develop a Flask web application which can be integrated into other packages and libraries, to create more complex and useful applications with a web interface easily.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Python Basics
Using a virtual environment with Python

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to:

  • Explain what Flask is and its benefits compared to other frameworks
  • Set up a development environment for Flask
  • Create a basic Flask application

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: The Capabilities of Flask

    Before we get to creating the web application with Flask, it is important to learn about Flask and why it could be a web development framework worth using.

    For a basic introduction, read the following articles for a quick overview of Flask and one of its integrations, Flask-SQLAlchemy.

    🔗 Everything you need to know about Flask for beginners

    🔗 Flask integration with SQLAlchemy

    Flask is a web microframework that is written in Python. The documentation lays out multiple benefits of using Flask, namely:

    • Its lightweightness, ease of extension in development, and integrations with other libraries
    • Its small learning curve
    • Its readability
  • Step 2: Installing Flask

    Now that you know a little more about Flask, it’s time to start developing! To begin, let’s create a development environment for your application. The virtual environment we will create will contain a self-contained Python environment with its own installation of Python, pip (Python package manager), and other necessary files. This allows you to install and manage Python packages specific to this project or environment without affecting your system-wide Python installation or other projects. Since Flask is coded in Python, users familiar with Python may find these steps familiar.

    If you have not, please install Python 3 and its package manager “pip”.

    For Windows users, you may do so at Python’s official website.

    For Mac users, enter the following command in your terminal.

    brew install python

    First, create a new folder for this campaign. In this new folder, create a folder named Quest1. In Quest1, create a folder named app and a file named requirements.txt. In the app folder, create a file named app.py. You should now have a file directory structure that looks like this:

    FlaskCampaign
   > Quest1
      > app
         > app.py
      > requirements.txt
    Plain text

    Next, open a terminal in the Quest1 directory and run the following command* to create a virtual environment for our quest. The venv module is a built-in module in Python used for creating virtual environments. Once the command is run, you will see the venv folder created. Note: If the command's output indicates that Python is not installed, you can replace python3 with python instead.

    python3 -m venv ./venv/

    Next, we will be using the following command to activate the virtual environment that we just created. Once the command runs, you will notice the prompt in your terminal change, which now includes (venv). This indicates that you are now working in the virtual environment.

    For Windows users

    .\venv\Scripts\activate.bat

    For MacOS and Linux users (including cloud development users)

    source ./venv/bin/activate

    Next, enter this into the file requirements.txt.

    Flask
    Plain text

    Then, run the following code in your terminal to install the required package that we listed in the requirements.txt file.

    pip3 install -r requirements.txt
  • Step 3: Creating Your First Flask Application

    Firstly, open app.py in your code editor, and enter this line.

    from flask import Flask
    Python

    This line imports the Flask module from the Flask library which you will use later.

    Next, initialise your application with this line. This creates a Flask application in which you can include functions.

    app = Flask(__name__)
    Python

    Now, let’s create the first route! In a typical website, your URL or link would look like this: https://www.examplewebsite.com/page  . In this case, the route is defined as “/”. Let’s try replicating that by entering this code snippet next.

    @app.route('/')
def hello_world():
    return 'Hello World!'
    Python

    This creates a route at “/” which will return the text “Hello World!”.

    And finally, let’s run the application with the following code.

    if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()
    Python

    Your final code in app.py should look like this.

    Save your file. In your terminal, change the present working directory to app and run app.py with this command in your terminal.

    python3 app.py

    Then open http://localhost:5000/

    You should see your website hosted on your computer and the message “Hello World!”.

  • Step 4: Hosting Your Application Publicly

    Now that you have Flask installed and created your first application, let’s try hosting it to make it accessible to others!

    We will be using Vercel, a free application hosting service that provides support for Flask.

    Firstly, create a Vercel account here if you do not have an account. Your username for Vercel should be the same or very similar to your StackUp username. You can change your username in the Personal Account Settings.

    After creating your account, go back to Visual Studio Code and run the following commands in your terminal to install the Vercel CLI utility. This requires npm which is installed together with Node.js.

    npm i -g vercel

    Then, run the following command in the Quest1 directory.

    vercel

    You may be first asked to login. You can do so using Continue with Email. An email will be sent to you and you will need to click on the 'Verify' button.

    You may follow the image below for the options to choose.

    Next, create the file vercel.json in the Quest1 directory with the following contents.

    {
    "version": 2,
    "builds": [
      {
        "src": "app/app.py",
        "use": "@vercel/python"
      }
    ],
    "routes": [
      {
        "src": "/(.*)",
        "dest": "app/app.py"
      }
    ]
}
    Plain text

    This file specifies that the application should be built with Python and to use /app/app.py as the file for the source code at any route.

    Lastly, in your terminal, run the vercel command again and your application should be deployed with a preview URL.

    Click on the Preview URL and you should be able to see your application live.

    Next, we want to ensure that our preview URL can be viewed by others. In your browser, head to Vercel and log in. Select the flask-quest1 project which you created earlier. Go to the Settings tab. Select Deployment Protection and disable Vercel Authentication. Be sure to click Save.

  • Step 5: (For Earn App) Let’s Ace Your Submissions! Prepare Your Submission!

    You have reached the end! Now to make sure you successfully complete this quest! There are 2 deliverables required for this quest – a screenshot and a web link. Make sure you complete both before submitting this quest!

    Screenshot

    Your screenshot should show:

    • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
    • app.py code
    • Terminal showing that your site has been deployed to Vercel, with the preview URL clearly shown. This URL should be the same URL that you will submit as a web link.
    • All parts shown in the 'expected output' image below.

    When labelling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided: C30_Q1_yourstackupname.png. Replace yourstackupname with your own StackUp profile name. 

    Web Link

    Submit the link to your deployed Vercel app. Ensure that your site shows 'Hello World!' and can be viewed by the public.
